From: Christopher L. Crutchfield <ccrutchf@ucsd.edu>
Date: Sat, 26 Apr 2026 17:30:00 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] ufs: exynos: preserve bootloader IOCC bits when
 !dma-coherent

Commit f92bb74 ("scsi: ufs: exynos: Disable iocc if dma-coherent
property isn't set") deliberately switched the !dma-coherent path
from no-op to "actively clear iocc bits". The intent — keep
hardware-coherency state consistent with what the kernel claims —
makes sense in isolation, but the chosen mechanism is destructive
to bootloader configuration on platforms where the IOCC bits
control more than just snoop participation.

When 'dma-coherent' is not set in DT, exynos_ufs_parse_dt sets
iocc_val=0 and exynos_ufs_shareability then issues
regmap_update_bits(sysreg, iocc_offset, iocc_mask, val=0), which
*actively clears* the IOCC sharability bits the bootloader set.

On gs201 (Tensor G2 / Pixel Fold) this is fatal: the IOCC bits at
sysreg_hsi2+0x710 don't just control hardware coherency, they also
control whether the UFS controller's AXI master uses Inner-Shareable
Normal-Memory transactions. With those bits cleared the controller
issues Device-Memory accesses that get absorbed by intermediate
buffers and never reach CPU-visible DRAM. Symptom: link startup
succeeds, every NOP_OUT "completes" (UTRCS fires, doorbell clears)
but the response slot in memory stays untouched (no UIC errors,
OCS=SUCCESS), proven by stamping the response slot with a magic
byte before submission and observing that the magic survives the
entire transaction.

Observed on a Pixel Fold (felix) running mainline:

  exynos-ufshc 14700000.ufs: sysreg-HSI2 IOCC before-iocc-write: @0x710 = 0x00000013
  exynos-ufshc 14700000.ufs: sysreg-HSI2 IOCC after-iocc-write : @0x710 = 0x00000010

Bootloader had bits 0 and 1 (RD/WR Sharable) set; mainline cleared them.

The fix preserves the bootloader's IOCC bits when 'dma-coherent' is
absent by zeroing iocc_mask instead of iocc_val. With mask=0 the
regmap_update_bits call becomes a no-op so any firmware-programmed
bits stay intact. Platforms that intentionally want IOCC bits cleared
should clear them in the bootloader; the kernel actively zeroing them
fights with that intent.

On gs201 the AOSP driver pairs `dma-coherent` with
`ufs-iocc { val = <0x3>; }` in DT; preserving rather than clearing
brings the !dma-coherent path in line with the same defensive
behavior. Note: this change does not on its own resolve the wider
mainline gs201 NOP_OUT failure (additional firewalls between the
controller and DRAM remain unresolved). It is sent as a targeted
correctness fix for the destructive-clear behavior, which likely
affects other Samsung platforms whose bootloaders configure IOCC
bits expected to persist into the kernel.

Cc: Peter Griffin <peter.griffin@linaro.org>
References: f92bb74 ("scsi: ufs: exynos: Disable iocc if dma-coherent property isn't set")
Signed-off-by: Christopher L. Crutchfield <ccrutchf@ucsd.edu>
---
 drivers/ufs/host/ufs-exynos.c | 13 +++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 11 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/ufs/host/ufs-exynos.c b/drivers/ufs/host/ufs-exynos.c
--- a/drivers/ufs/host/ufs-exynos.c
+++ b/drivers/ufs/host/ufs-exynos.c
@@ -1352,10 +1352,19 @@ static int exynos_ufs_parse_dt(struct device *dev, struct exynos_ufs *ufs)
 	ufs->iocc_mask = ufs->drv_data->iocc_mask;
 	/*
 	 * no 'dma-coherent' property means the descriptors are
-	 * non-cacheable so iocc shareability should be disabled.
+	 * non-cacheable so kernel-side cache maintenance handles
+	 * coherency. Don't actively *clear* the IOCC bits in that
+	 * case: zero the mask so the subsequent regmap_update_bits
+	 * call is a no-op, preserving whatever the firmware/bootloader
+	 * configured. On some platforms (e.g. gs201/Tensor G2) the
+	 * IOCC bits also control whether the controller's AXI master
+	 * uses Inner-Shareable Normal-Memory transactions; clearing
+	 * them turns master writes into Device-Memory accesses that
+	 * never reach CPU-visible DRAM, producing silent UPIU
+	 * completion failures (NOP OUT response slot stays untouched).
 	 */
 	if (of_dma_is_coherent(dev->of_node))
 		ufs->iocc_val = ufs->iocc_mask;
 	else
-		ufs->iocc_val = 0;
+		ufs->iocc_mask = 0;

 	ufs->pclk_avail_min = PCLK_AVAIL_MIN;
--
2.50.0
